Ask HN: Light weight architectures for ChatGPT-based web app
text:
As AI applications are suddenly booming due to the recent development of AI model such as ChatGPT. I'm wondering what are the best/typical light weight architectures and tech stacks for ChatGPT-based web apps such as https://chat.openai.com/ so that we can rapidly test a lot of ideas.

I knew/researched some options below but not sure what's the typical combination of them or some further details.

- Frontend: React/Vue/Angular. Easy to decide (hint: ask ChatGPT). But how about UI frameworks/libraries? where to host it? vercel?

- Backend: Node.js? is express.js still a good/typical choice? but how about Serverless? Do we need Socket.io alike frameworks to do chat(bot) based web apps? where to host the backend? vercel can do the job too or AWS or GAE?

- DB: traditional DB or Firebase alike?

How to create the web app project? I guess it's frontend or backend framework dependent.

Sorry for those beginner questions as my tech background is limited to my iOS + some Java + some RoR days.

More Airbnb Problems
text:
Is there any recourse against Airbnb when they don't refund your money as promised, or when they don't refund in accordance with their policies? I've had two situations in the past year where Airbnb Support passes me from person to person and then never refunds my money.

Short of opening a dispute with the bank, is there any process to have a well-trained person take a look at a reservation? Or is the only solution to let them steal my money and stop using the platform...

Ask HN: Does anyone else notice Joe Rogan using dark pattern advertising?
text:
This is a good example:

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2EgPGQmhWag

This is obviously a Dan Carlin ad. I noticed one recently where he just asks the guest about their glasses, and the guest proceeds to straight up advertise a website that sells those glasses.

It feels like a very disingenuous way of advertising and it's happening more and more.
